segments.text: Go back to question one.
When and where were you in Vietnam?
67 to late 68.
We were boarded from Seattle, Washington to Battalion.
We spent about 21 days going across.
We landed in the Philippine Islands, Subi Beach.
From there, it was about three days.
And we landed in Bontown.
It's about 15, 20 miles from Saigon.
From there, we were airlifted to Bengua, which at that time, Bengua was just an airstrip in 1967.
Later, it was expanded.
When I came back, we flew out of Bengua, and it was more like a big airstrip.
Then while we went into a long time, the base camp there was known as Bear Camp, home of the 9th Infantry.
It was a division coming from Kansas City to Kansas.
And you probably recall the mobile airlift.
OK, that was a division that was airlifted from Kansas in 1966.
So we went there as a supporting unit to back up the Thailand
soldiers coming in from Thailand.
Before we got there, it was just junk.
That was it.
We went in there to clear the area for them.
And late, uh, back in early September, that's when the base camp was already secured.
And they came in under, Westmoreland was there.
He was the guy that brought them in.
And from there, we just did our regular search, destroyed.
Our firefighters came about 30, 40 miles from that area.
We protected more mainly the long, thin properties, which was Cuxi, Bensal, La Trang.
Six or seven different families.
A lot of them were just villages.
Highway 1 was just a dirt road.
You know, you could just, maybe one vehicle at a time.
When we left, I left way back in 68, May 68.
The road was expanded, maybe where you could have two vehicles.
And it was mainly for, there was no one-way tracks.
Everything was there.
We had the personal carriers running around, the artillery, tanks, everything.
Engineering equipment was going all over the place.
And some of those things happened.
Okay.
How did you feel at the time, back in 66, 67, when you went to serve in Vietnam, what you were doing?
In 66, 65, really, I was going to school.
Then after, I dropped out.
When I went to work in the 40s.
So I ended up in Chicago.
working with Western Vet Company.
But all this time, I knew about the Vietnam War, what was going on, or the war.
And when the draft started to come around, and I knew I was going to be up to it.
In fact, I even received a letter from President Johnson.
I went ahead and volunteered the draft.
And I came all the way to McAllen.
I could have come from upstate.
But I knew there was a lot of guys here that were going to be also drafted.
So I tried to come down to Macau or West Lake, or Mercedes and maybe get it, I mean, go as a buddy system type.
But going into the war or going into the Vietnam crisis, that was, I think what I was just looking for, to go in there and help out.
or be part of it.
There was no doubt in my mind I was gonna let down or I was gonna find an excuse to get out of it.
You know another thing that a lot of us that served, or my age, we came from a military family background.
My uncle served in World War II Korea.
So that's had to do a lot with our attitude, pointing to this thing here, being patriotic to the cause.
And probably being because of Americano, Chicano heritage, we kind of look up to keeping our own traditions going.
And I think most of the Mexicans that served, that I knew from California, Nevada, all the Southwest had the same feeling.
You know, there was never a guy in my mind that when we went out on patrol that wanted to cop out.
We all stayed together.
There were about four or five of us.
But talking to some of the guys in different areas, they had the same feeling.
And the same thing went for the blacks and the whites.
I mean, we were all working together.
We made 66, 67, 68 people there who had no resent against
what we were doing there.
I think we all believed that we were doing it for one reason, and that we were serving the country.
And they were living to those standards that were laid back by other generations.
They had served in World War II, South Pacific, across Europe.
Maybe that's the way I feel, and I still feel the same way.
If I had to do it again, hey, I would go back and I would probably do the same thing.

You mentioned that some of your friends around here felt pretty bad they were rejected by the... You know, as a matter of fact, a lot of us, I still remember very vividly when we left McCallum and we were in the
VTC bus was provided for us.
A lot of them were rejected.
They didn't want to come back.
They felt bad about it.
They wanted to stay.
They wanted to stay.
What was the reason behind that?
Can you explain that?
The guy was rejected.
Physically?
Yeah.
Why?
Why they felt bad?
Well, they felt that...
I guess peer pressure, the way we were raised.
Most of the guys that I knew were athletes.
We played ball together.
We did all those things in school.
Did you think you played an important role in Vietnam?
Well, yeah, I think so.

First thing that, you know, from my own personal view and the way I was raised, you know, being there and seeing what I saw with the people there, it's kind of like seeing yourself back home, you know, with poverty.
The whole life standards
maybe you can say 20, 30 years behind that time compared to the United States.
So coming from our area, you could see that, hey, this is the same thing that could happen back in the States.
Poverty, the whole aspect was just trying to help people over there and maybe show them, hey,
We are here to help you, and if you understand our ways, maybe we can overthrow whatever the government is trying to take over you guys.
Basically, that's what it is.
The economic aspect.
What I saw there, and the things we were trying to accomplish is, I think basically it was to help the village people.

even if we could just educate them a little bit and and work on their own necessity you know survive that's what i kind of transpired to or i wanted to leave that behind you know not necessarily the american gi or because we had australians there people from korea and thailand they were all doing that
for the same cause, helping the people.
I think that was my main idea was we were there, and we're going to treat these people here like we treated our own back home.
But being from the Valley, did you find things, was it easier to relate to these people who were poor?
Yeah, well, you could always see yourself, like,

Since we're close to Mexico, and you're almost different, the same atmosphere about going across the border and seeing the things that happen there is the same thing that happens in undeveloped countries.
And basically, that's how we see those people there.
Exactly, if you go across right now, go to those villages out there, you see the same thing right now.
And that's how I think it was a carry over 10,000 miles away from here.
And basically, that's how we look things up.
I mean, people that came from the valley.
We had other guys that, of course, came from the Middle States.
They couldn't understand that.
because of their background.
But I think the Mexicans that went over there had a better understanding of why these people were living the way they did.
Basically, it was education had to play a vital part.
People tried to understand.
What did you think of the US military during the war when you were over there?
The military aspect I think was very strong, very, very strong feelings.
We were there and we felt that we were the best.
That the army, that the whole armed forces were very, not rigid, but strong.
Nothing was gonna stop us.
We had the power, we had the knowledge.
I think the most important part was being patriotic to the cause.
You wanted to be part of that.
I feel that every person that served at that time felt the same way.
I don't recall, none of those guys are about
the riots going back on or anything like that.
We felt very strong about the armed forces.
And we felt like, hey, we're part of it.
Did you encounter any problems in Vietnam because you were a Chicano or Hispanic?
Not in Vietnam.
There was a little bit of it here in the States.
basic training for the poor population.
Most of your Hispanics went to Fort Paul.
And it was, you know, maybe you can call it little things.
It was in the enlistment personnel.
And of course, you're gonna have names calling, you know, a greaser, and gringo, and negro, black.
But mainly it was under that range of the young guys, the 18, 19 years old.
Not from the superiors?
Not from the high rank, or the people that were there, the drill sergeants.
And if they did call you, it was trying to see how much pressure you could take, or see what was your response to something like that.
I think it was just more trying to test you.
You know, I was called dirty Mexican.
And I didn't respond back to him when I was taking this surgery.
I think it had to do with how we were raised, you know, from my home, you know, with a lot of respect and stuff like that.
And we knew that the real surgeon was going to come after us hard, trying to weave out the guy that was, you know, not supportive towards us.
But that's the only encounter I had.
as, you know, discrimination.
But I don't call it discrimination.
It was more like harassment.
But in Vietnam there was more unity?
Vietnam was a completely different thing.
It was more like we're a family back there.
You know, we stick together.
You could tell black, brown, white.
Man, in fact, most of my best buddies were white.
Blacks.
We all drank together.
We drank together, we slept together, and fought together.
And we protected each other.
We were very close.
We volunteered.
When one guy volunteered for my squad, everybody wanted to volunteer.
We all wanted to be together.
We went to a village for recreation.
We went for recreation.
We kind of looked pretty short.
We wrote letters.
Some guys couldn't write, so I would sit down with them and I would write the letters.
I know a guy from Utah, John Baswell.
John Bowen.
He couldn't write.
It was about nine years old.
So I used to write his letters.
You know, just mine.
So I took care of his quality.
Of course, I was 21 years old, so I was considered a little bit older.
So I was 17, 18 years old.
So they look up to my age, I guess, because I was a little bit older, like the big brother type.
And I was a little bit more mature.
I took care of those little kids.
The youngest was a kid from North Carolina, Billy Graham.
He was 17 years old.
You know, he always
He always wanted to be with me, because he knew that I was very disciplined on my ways.
I wanted to come back home.
I was married, and I had a little girl back home.
And I told the guy, hey, man, I got something to go home.
So I guess that kind of helped him out.
They took care of what we were trying to do.
So there was no drug fit.
And if there were drugs, they hide it.
Nothing like back in the 70s, whatever.
67, 68, we were very serious about the war.
I know the American soldiers.
What was there was very serious.
I don't think casualties-wise were that prolonged tremendously way back in those years.
We were very careful about it.
People got careless maybe later in the late part of the Vietnam War.
But, you know, talking from experience, I don't think we, casualty-wise, was not because we were careless, you know, what we were doing.
We were trained, and I think we went ahead and performed like people wanted us to perform.
doing our job.
And nothing, we gave it 100%.
That's what we're working on.
How have your views changed since the time you were in Vietnam, if any?
To the press?
Yeah.
You know, here we were in 1986.
1966 is 20 years ago.
To me, you can see it and you can break it down into two parts.
When I came back, it's not hate, but it was something that people were blaming the American soldier for something that they were doing that on reality can be happening right now.
to our own people.
But I guess the only people that can understand that face is the soldier that was there, that understands that Vietnam, that war is not just fighting.
You have to fight all kinds of things.
Poverty is one thing.
Abuse.
That's part of war.
The nearest people never bring their stuff out.
They always tell you how many guys died.
They never tell you what it's called behind the scenes.
And that's what's worse.
When I look at people taking advantage of what we have, which is freedom, they really don't know what they have until they lose it.
And that's telling you that some guy coming in and saying, hey, tomorrow you're going to die.
That's what I'm talking about.
And I hope it will never happen here, but something like that bothers me.
We have Nicaragua today.
And I always have felt it.
And Vietnam was an example for us.
We could have stopped communist aggression there.
If the politicians only knew what goes on the battlegrounds, they don't know.
They need to be there.
Then they will probably realize, hey, if we don't stop them right there, 1,500 miles from here, hey, they're going to be right there behind our back door.
I guarantee you that.
That's the way it works.
And we had a chance in Vietnam.
And Vietnam was 10,000 miles away from home.
Now we're down 1,500 miles.
And that's scary.
That is scary.
So I don't know what can happen.
I don't know, maybe they envy the American people.
Maybe they envy the American lifestyle.
I think they do.
You know, it's, communist people, communists, they hate the American GI.
I know that.
And I don't know if you've heard commentaries from Libya or Castro, and they say our dream is to come and conquer the American people.
They will not destroy it, because they want to take it as intact, because we have built so much.
They're not going to bum it out.
They're not going to blow it.
They want to take it while they're serving people because they like what we do.
And talking about being 20 years and thinking now about what we have, we don't protect it now.
And here we got a lot of young people coming out, young men.
And you ask them about the armed services,
Hey, they have a very negative attitude.
They have a very negative attitude.
But if you ask them, do you enjoy lifestyle, about the American lifestyle, that someone will nod their head and some guys can't even answer to.
Because you know what you're going to ask them next time.
If we enjoy peace, hey, we're going to pay the price for it.
Even if you have to give your life out there.
Somebody has to.
But again, it's not fair that only a very few can do it, where others can relax back and enjoy the rest of their lives.
And that's what worries me, and that's what I think upsets me a lot.
The Vietnam crisis had to do a lot with it.
You know, deformative, college deformatives, rev dodgers.
All those people now are 42, 43, 44, 45 years old.
Some of those guys are in Congress right now.
But if you ask them, what were you when Vietnam was going on and what the heck were you doing?
They give you a negative attitude or a negative answer.
I've talked to ex-people.
They can never give you a straight answer.
Not now.
And they never will.
Maybe they were ashamed of me, you know.
Say, hey, I have heard people say, hey, I wanted to go, but they never called for me.
You know.
And I ask, but hey, I didn't call.
I mean, I got a call, but hey, I went ahead and took it.
I said, I'm willing to go now.
I took the risk.
And maybe people don't want to do that nowadays.
They're afraid to take the number one step.
Serve your country.
And I guarantee you, you'll feel better about it.
My family, they're very proud.
They're very proud that I served.
They have never given me a negative attitude.
They have never said, why did I serve?
I think their own reasonings or their own
views, the way I feel, is carried on to my daughters, you know, because they want to pursue into the armed forces.
So, and then I guess the tradition has been carried on from my father to the military.
Okay.
You had two brothers in Vietnam, two other brothers that served in Vietnam.
Did they have the same reasons for being out there?
Basically, it was the same reasons that I just finished telling you.
He was the family background.
My other brother's twin brother.
And we always compete, athletics, school, whatever.
But I always have felt that the reason he went to Vietnam because I had served.
And he was in college, and he could stay.
And he was a junior in Pan American when he decided to join.
And I was still there.
I was in Vietnam in 68.
He was in the court place in Paso in 68.
When I got back, as soon as I got back, he put a 1049, go Vietnam.
And he went, he was here.
And then he came back.
I was in school.
I went back to school on the GI.
And talking about competing, I was behind by two years.
So I told him, when he got back, hey, I challenge you.
I want to try to finish school before you do.
And he only had about a month to go, or maybe a semester.
But anyway, he went ahead and graduated in May, and I graduated in August.
And my other brother, he's the youngest, he also volunteered.
He served in Korea.
And then he, at that time, my brother was in Vietnam.
So I guess for reasons, as soon as he left Vietnam, he also served.
One of them had served.
So we had three brothers, myself and two more.
And my family never did complain.
My mom never did protest or never wrote the congressman's here or the representative about having three sons serve in Vietnam.
I guess my dad never wanted that.
And he never did brag about it.
No, he died two years ago.
And he never said, when we all came back, he never said nothing about how was the war.
I guess he, on his own ways of doing things, he felt proud.
And of course, all his brothers were veterans.
So I guess that's how he pictured the whole thing.
That tradition is still what's going on.
It carried on through us.
And if there's another war, hey, maybe some guys will be part of our family, probably doing the same thing.
Because I think all our relatives are our family.
They feel the same way.
serving the country.
What did you think of the Vietnamese people when you were over there?
The Vietnamese, they wanted the G.I.
to be there.
Economically, it was one of them.
They were friendly.
And basically what I'm talking about is the villagers, the old people.
I never saw the young guys, the young men.
They were probably in the unfortunate.
The contact that we had was mainly with the papasan, the namasan, the kids.

and I you know they treated us like hey you're the number one GI you know especially Hispanics that you know dark-skinned Hispanics they kind of look up to us like you're big you're strong and I guess we were more like a model to them that hey it can happen you can win the sport and they believe us they had a lot of trust so
They had us there, you know, like something good had happened to them.
And it bothers me a little bit when we're going back to the three-brother store in Vietnam.
You know, it's, you know, being a parent now,
I just wonder how my parents felt having three sons back to back.
It's a worried aspect.
And then you wonder about the people that protest the war.
They saw that little people that had relatives
brothers, sisters, whatever some girls say.
In my mind, they never had a doubt in their mind about the family, what they were going through.
And so it's putting the GI down.
And maybe we learn a lesson today.
If we're going to get involved in another conflict, maybe to me,
If people want to protest, then they don't belong in this country.
That's what I feel.
Because they like the American style of living.
Hey, you shouldn't have no questions on my mind.
Hey, why should you go against things that we're trying to accomplish in other places?
But hey, man, it can happen here.
I guarantee you that.
I guarantee you that.
And when you see, you know, people like in Vietnam that were killed and all this other stuff that happened, rape for one thing, then you wonder.
You wonder about it.
And I guess what makes a complete different person, the GI they have served,
But we know from firsthand, because we were there and we saw it.
And we can feel it, what can happen overnight.
I could see it right now.
I could see somebody out there behind my backyard.
And it bothers me.
It really bothers me.
Sometimes I go out there, sightseeing, behind our backyard, and I go behind our backyard to Rio Grande do Rio right there, Rio.
And I just, you know, in my mind I could just see people coming across.
Infiltration.
And that's how it starts.
And people that come, they call this all this riot and stuff, you know, it's all communists.
And they're not going to get through military faces.
They're going to go through education or other aspects of communist tactics.
And I think that's one of the ways they penetrate the society of the American people, by getting all this information into the public, whether it's the media or TV media or whatever.
Here, Reagan is asking for $100 million.
Hey, my point of view, hey, give him the $100 million.
Hey, it's money.
When you start putting lives out there and you start losing lives, now how much is $100 million going to cover one?
Hey, money, that becomes a very, it's a little thing.
You know, it's becoming a, you know, if the guy wants $100 million, give it to him.
Give him that.
When you start putting military personnel, people are going to get hurt.
And I can see it right now.
And it's not going to be 100 or 200 casualties.
It was back, but Vietnam had, you know, right there.
So here we, you know, I think the GI, the guy that was really involved in the military, they can tell you right now,
When it comes to money, you can't buy lots of money.
